# Agent Notes

- To run the OS in QEMU, use `make run-hdd`.
  - Prefer this over `make run`; the HDD target is the intended path for interactive runs.
- If you run `make run-hdd`, you won't be able to continue, because the process won't finish.  If you want to run it then kill it to get serial output, run `killall qemu-system-x86_64`
- Standard build remains `make` (produces `os.img` and `hdd.img`).
- We have our own libc implementation (src/kernel/libc.c), and memory/heap management (malloc, calloc, realloc, free) in src/kernel/heap.c.  Use heap operations rather than trying to use fixed memory assigned in stage2.asm unless absolutely necessary.
- If you need to modify memory layout, make sure you keep STAGE2_BASE and STACK_TOP up-to-date to avoid smashing memory through overlaps in stage2.asm
- If you want to boot the kernel, the shell has a variety of commands (including shutdown) - which you can use to stop the kernel and return to your thinking

Thanks!

**State Check**  
- Every shell command is still a kernel function in the build (see the `$(wildcard $(SBIN_DIR)/*.c)` glob folded into the kernel objects in `Makefile:27`).  
- The shell only knows about commands that appear in the static table at `src/sbin/shell.c:256`, and it runs them by spawning kernel threads via `process_create_kernel_with_parent` before returning the buffered output (`src/sbin/shell.c:387`).  
- There is no code path that ever marks a process as user-mode; `allocate_process` always leaves `proc->is_user = false` (`src/kernel/process.c:378`), so the scheduler, paging, and exception paths are all written assuming ring0 execution (`src/kernel/process.c:948`).  

**Suggested Path**  
- **Carve Out User Processes First**  Extend `process_create_*` so you can set `proc->is_user = true` and build a user stack/trap frame that returns to ring3 with `GDT_SELECTOR_USER_*` (`include/arch/x86/segments.h:4`). That also means giving `paging_clone_kernel_space` helpers to map user pages with the `PAGE_USER` bit (`src/arch/x86/paging.c:214`) and switching `cr3` per process instead of sharing the kernel tables. Start with a dummy user thread that just `exit(0)` to prove the privilege drop works before touching ELF.  
- **Add an ELF Loader Module**  Create something like `src/kernel/elf.c` that can parse an ELF64 image read from VFS (grab bytes with `vfs_data` from `include/vfs.h:18`) and map each `PT_LOAD` segment into the target address space. Youll need utility routines to allocate zeroed physical pages (identity-mapped heap works for now) and to apply the right RWX + user flags when inserting them into the new page tables.  
- **Define a Minimal Syscall ABI**  Once you can jump to ring3 you must give user code a way to talk to the kernel. Pick an entry mechanism (`int 0x80` via a new IDT vector in `src/arch/x86/interrupts.c:121` is the quickest) and expose syscalls for at least `write`, `exit`, `open/read/close`, and maybe `sbrk`. Wire those through the existing FD layer (`src/kernel/fd.c:19`) so that shell I/O redirection keeps working.  
- **Split the C Runtime**  The current libc implementation is compiled into the kernel (`src/kernel/libc.c`, referenced everywhere). Move the portable pieces into a shared library (or copy them) so you can build userland objects plus a tiny `crt0` that sets up argc/argv and invokes `main` before issuing the `exit` syscall.  
- **Rework the Build + Shell Integration**  Teach the top-level `Makefile` to build user programs into ELF binaries (e.g., `build/user/<cmd>.elf`), copy them into a `/bin` directory inside whatever filesystem image you mount, and remove their `.c` files from the kernel object glob. In the shell, after the built-in table at `src/sbin/shell.c:256` fails, fall back to resolving `/bin/<name>` via `vfs_resolve` (`include/vfs.h:20`) and invoke a new `exec_elf(path, args, stdout_fd)` helper that wraps your loader/`process_create_user`. Keep built-ins around until each command has been ported.  

**Next Steps**  
1. Prototype `process_create_user()` that drops into ring3 with a fake stub function; verify the trapframe/iret path works.  
2. Implement the ELF loader and map a trivial Hello, world binary that only uses your new `write`/`exit` syscalls.  
3. Convert one simple command (e.g., `echo`) into a user-space ELF, hook `/bin/echo`, and let the shell use it as a proof-of-concept before migrating the rest.

**ELF + User Mode**
- Added per-process user mappings and user-stack trampolines so we can drop into ring3: `paging_map_user_page()` etc. in src/arch/x86/paging.c:481-580 and the new user-thread path/process factory logic in src/kernel/process.c:1087-1265 keep threads suspended until the ELF image is loaded, expose `process_address_space()`, and let us enqueue user processes later.  
- Wired an actual int0x80 path via src/arch/x86/syscall_entry.S:1-33 and src/kernel/syscall.c:1-51 so exit/read/write/close now work, while open/sbrk still return ENOSYS placeholders.

**ELF Loader & Userland**
- Introduced exec_spawn_elf() plus the ELF/stack helpers in src/kernel/exec.c:1-420: program headers get validated, PT_LOAD segments are paged into the new address space, and argc/argv/envp stacks are synthesized before scheduling the suspended user process.
- Built a tiny user toolchain (crt0/libc/syscall stubs) with its own linker script; see user/crt0.c:1-11, user/libc.c:1-71, user/echo.c:1-15, and user/link.ld. The top-level Makefile:40-98 now compiles these, links them as position-dependent ELF64 images at 0x100400000, and objcopys them into blob objects that are part of the kernel link.
- At boot, embedded binaries are written into the in-memory FS (`/bin/echo` for now) via src/kernel/userbin.c:1-61, and kernel_main() calls userbin_populate() right after vfs_init() (src/kernel/kernel.c:20-50).

**Shell Updates**
- The shell still dispatches built-ins, but now tries ELF binaries before printing unknown command: see the external-exec path in src/sbin/shell.c:366-535. Arguments are tokenized, VFS lookups search `/bin/<cmd>` when no slash is provided, and we fall back gracefully if the file is missing or the ELF load fails.
- Helper plumbing (src/sbin/shell.c:560-760) builds argv arrays, resolves paths, and, when `>` redirection is used, allocates a temporary fd backed by vfs_append via the new fd_ops so user processes can redirect stdout without touching shell buffers.

- `make -s` (clean build of kernel + user binaries + embedded blobs).

1. Flesh out user-visible syscalls (implement open/close on top of VFS and provide at least a stub sbrk/heap API) so richer user programs can run.
2. Start migrating the other shell utilities from src/sbin/ into `user/` binaries and extend the `/bin` population table accordingly.
